46    /**
47    * Computes the set of possible concrete types for every variable, property,
48    * function argument, and function return value in the program. Unlike a normal
49    * reference type annotation, a concrete type of A indicates that an instance of
50    * A -- not a subclass of A -- is a possible value.
51    *
52    * Also unlike normal type checking, this pass does not assume that all defined
53    * functions are actually called. Instead, it assumes only that the top-level
54    * code is executed plus any implicit calls detected, such as calls to functions
55    * exported via goog.exportSymbol or Element.addEventListener. Hence, this pass
56    * also performs a very strict form of dead code detection. Elimination of dead
57    * code will occur because the disambiguation pass can rename all uncalled
58    * functions to have distinct names, which will then appear to be uncalled to
59    * the normal unused property remover.
60    *
61    * Since concrete types are all reference types, we only care about the limited
62    * set of actions that apply to them: assignments to variables/properties,
63    * method calls, and return statements. To speed up and simplify the
64    * implementation, the first time a scope is processed, we make one pass through
65    * it {@link CreateScope} to translate it into a list of Actions. Each Action
66    * can translate itself into a list of assignments: method calls are just
67    * assignments to the parameter variables, while return statements are
68    * assignments to a special $return slot. Each time a scope is (re-)processed,
69    * we iterate over the assignments produced by the actions and update the types
70    * of the target slots. Once we complete a pass through all scopes with no
71    * changes, we are done.
72    *
73    */
